title: Add shardspec for hash based sharding and determine shard count by cardinality estimation
body:
This pull request introduces support for random sharding by estimating cardinality of input data set using HyperLogLog and distributing the rows in shards on the basis on hashcode, Random sharding has two major improvements over singleDimension sharding -  
1) Better distribution of data resulting in almost equal sized partitions, thus achieving better query parallelism.
2) The mapper Job for cardinality estimation does very less Hadoop IO and thus is much more efficient than single dimension sharding.

Changes  - 
1) Support for Random Sharding
2) New PartitionSpec type introduced for random sharding 
3) Support for determining interval in determine partitions

title: Bridge Multiple Druid Clusters
body:
This pull request introduces the following:
- changes to the rules such that a single rule may apply to multiple tiers
- introduces 'forever' rules such that a rule may not always need a notion of "time" associated with it
- introduces a 'bridge' node to encapsulate the idea that one entire Druid cluster can appear to be a single node to another Druid cluster
- all queryable nodes can now announce their priority and the broker can select which nodes to query based on priority, this is for replication of segments across tiers
- this PR is backwards compatible
- tests
- docs to be added once things are verified to be stable
- GUI still needs some work

title: Remove unused payload column from sub-select that fails in postgres.  Use ...
body:
...boolean true/false for 'used' column so that queries run in postgres.

I am using postgres instead of mysql for the druid relational store.  I found and fixed two issues:

First, in DatabaseRuleManager.java#poll, selecting the payload column in the sub-select causes an error:

druid=> SELECT dataSource, max(version) as version, payload FROM druid_rules GROUP BY dataSource;
ERROR:  column "druid_rules.payload" must appear in the GROUP BY clause or be used in an aggregate function
LINE 1: SELECT dataSource, max(version) as version, payload FROM dru...

The inner payload column doesn't seem to be used so I removed it.

Second, in DatabaseSegmentManager I changed used=0 and used=1 to used=false/used=true.  Postgres does not cast 1/0 to true/false.

title: Indexing service stuff
body:
_Don't merge yet! Tests don't pass!_

The TaskQueue directly manages the TaskRunner. The main management loop runs
periodically and checks that the runner is doing reasonable things. If not, it
attempts to adjust the runner. The management loop also runs on-demand when a
task is added to keep task assignment relatively low latency. The TaskConsumer
is no longer necessary and so it no longer exists.

Task interval locks are handled differently. Instead of some tasks acquiring
locks at runtime and some tasks having implicit fixed lock intervals, all tasks
ask for locks explicitly. This occurs either in "isReady" (which runs on the
overlord) or in "run" (which runs on the peon).

Other changes:
- The TaskQueue is attached to the leader lifecycle, instead of global
- The TaskLockbox is able to sync itself from storage and is no longer
  bootstrapped by the TaskQueue.
- RemoteTaskRunner does not clean up zk paths until asked to. This will
  prevent deletion of statuses that have not yet been committed.
- Added retries on DbTaskStorage operations.
- Removed SpawnTasksAction (no more subtasks)
- Removed obsolete EventReceiverFirehose configs
- Removed obsolete OldOverlordResource
- Removed TaskStorageQueryAdapter methods related to subtasks

title: Bard Results Cache implementation
body:
Caching Client is used for query results from druid server so its hard to use same for Bard Results Cache, so implemented a new caching client ResultsCachingClient to cache the merged results.
1. Cache keys include the segment identifier and version. Is this enough to make sure that if segments are removed/updated then keys will be different?
2. A different cache is used for results cache which should emit stats for bard result cache hits/misses.
3. The client is lifecycle managed and also registers for Segment Call back.

Pull request for 0.5.x version for now. Will make the changes for 0.6 once implementation is reviewed and agreed upon.

Most people will glance at intro pages (if they even land there ... see Google), and giving them the sexiest and most succinct info (i.e., the Key Features bullets) up top will help them quickly digest what's most salient (i.e., why should I really care). The following why/when/etc. are great too for those who get pulled in.

title: Fix HadoopDruidIndexer to work with the new way of things
body:
There are multiple and sundry changes in here.

First, "HadoopDruidIndexer" has been split into two pieces, (1) CliHadoop which pulls the hadoop version and builds up the right classpath with the proper hadoop version to run the indexer and (2) CliInternalHadoopIndexer which actually runs the indexer.

In order to work around a bunch of jets3t version conflicts with Hadoop and Druid, I needed to extract the S3 deep storage stuff into its own module.  I then also moved the HDFS stuff into its own module so that I could eliminate the dependency on Hadoop for druid-server.

In doing these changes, I wanted to make the extensions buildable with only the druid-api jar, so a few other things had to move out of Druid and into druid-api.  They are all API-level things, however, so they really belong in druid-api instead.

Lastly, I removed the druid-realtime module and put it all in druid-server.
